# Java 8+ Features: Lambda Expressions, Functional Interfaces, and Streams Introduction

## Lambda Expressions — Anonymous Functions
A lambda is a short anonymous function: `(parameters) -> expression`. It replaces verbose anonymous inner class syntax.

```java
// Before Java 8 — anonymous inner class for Comparator
Collections.sort(orders, new Comparator<Order>() {
    @Override
    public int compare(Order a, Order b) {
        return a.getTotal().compareTo(b.getTotal());
    }
});

// Java 8 lambda — same logic, one line
Collections.sort(orders, (a, b) -> a.getTotal().compareTo(b.getTotal()));

// Even cleaner — method reference
orders.sort(Comparator.comparing(Order::getTotal));
```

Lambda syntax:
```java
() -> "no params, returns string"
x -> x * 2              // one param, no braces
(x, y) -> x + y         // two params
(int x, int y) -> {     // block body (explicit return required)
    int sum = x + y;
    return sum;
}
```

## Functional Interfaces — Lambda Targets
Every lambda implements exactly one functional interface. Key built-in ones:
```java
// Predicate<T>: T -> boolean
Predicate<String> isLong = s -> s.length() > 10;
isLong.test("hello world!"); // true
isLong.and(s -> s.startsWith("H")).test("Hello World!"); // true (both conditions)

// Function<T,R>: T -> R
Function<String, Integer> strLen = String::length; // method reference
strLen.apply("hello"); // 5
Function<Integer, Integer> doubled = n -> n * 2;
strLen.andThen(doubled).apply("hello"); // 10 (compose: length then double)

// Consumer<T>: T -> void
Consumer<String> print = System.out::println;
print.accept("hello"); // prints hello

// Supplier<T>: () -> T
Supplier<List<String>> listFactory = ArrayList::new;
List<String> newList = listFactory.get(); // new ArrayList

// BiFunction<T,U,R>: (T,U) -> R
BiFunction<String, Integer, String> repeat = (s, n) -> s.repeat(n);
repeat.apply("ab", 3); // "ababab"
```

## Method References — Even More Concise
```java
String::toUpperCase          // instance method on the parameter
String::new                  // constructor reference
System.out::println          // instance method on a specific object
Integer::parseInt            // static method
list::add                    // instance method on captured variable
```
Use when the lambda just calls a single existing method.

## Streams Introduction — Declarative Data Processing
A Stream is a pipeline of operations on a sequence of elements. It does NOT store data — it processes data from a source (collection, array, file).

```java
List<Order> orders = ...;

// Imperative (old way)
List<Order> pendingOrders = new ArrayList<>();
for (Order o : orders) {
    if (o.getStatus().equals("PENDING")) {
        pendingOrders.add(o);
    }
}
Collections.sort(pendingOrders, Comparator.comparing(Order::getTotal).reversed());

// Declarative (streams) — same result, readable as English
List<Order> pendingOrders = orders.stream()
    .filter(o -> o.getStatus().equals("PENDING"))    // intermediate
    .sorted(Comparator.comparing(Order::getTotal).reversed()) // intermediate
    .collect(Collectors.toList());                    // terminal — triggers execution
```

**Intermediate operations (lazy, return Stream):** `filter`, `map`, `flatMap`, `sorted`, `distinct`, `limit`, `skip`
**Terminal operations (trigger execution, return result):** `collect`, `count`, `findFirst`, `anyMatch`, `allMatch`, `reduce`, `forEach`

**Streams are lazy:** intermediate operations build a pipeline but nothing executes until a terminal operation is called.

## Key Stream Operations
```java
// map — transform each element
List<String> names = orders.stream()
    .map(Order::getCustomerName)
    .collect(Collectors.toList());

// filter + findFirst + Optional
Optional<Order> firstLarge = orders.stream()
    .filter(o -> o.getTotal().compareTo(new BigDecimal("1000")) > 0)
    .findFirst(); // returns Optional<Order>

// reduce — fold
BigDecimal total = orders.stream()
    .map(Order::getTotal)
    .reduce(BigDecimal.ZERO, BigDecimal::add);

// groupingBy — creates Map<K, List<V>>
Map<String, List<Order>> byStatus = orders.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Order::getStatus));

// counting per group
Map<String, Long> countByStatus = orders.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Order::getStatus, Collectors.counting()));
```

## Connection to Angular and Spring Boot
Angular's RxJS Observables have the same pipeline philosophy: `observable.pipe(filter(...), map(...), take(5))`.
Spring Boot services use streams extensively for transforming entity lists to DTOs:
```java
return orderRepository.findAll().stream()
    .map(this::toDto)
    .collect(Collectors.toList());
```

## Common Mistakes
1. **Reusing a stream:** a stream can only be consumed once. Using it after a terminal operation throws `IllegalStateException: stream has already been operated upon`.
2. **Modifying source during stream:** streams assume the source is not modified during iteration.
3. **`forEach` for transformations:** `forEach` is for side effects; use `map` + `collect` to build new lists.
4. **`null` in streams:** `NullPointerException` if `map()` returns null and downstream operations call methods on it. Use `filter(Objects::nonNull)` or `flatMap`.

